<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06234034 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06234034 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  FOOD; RECIPE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  MANY of us can't understand the fascination with mint jelly on lamb. It isalways too green, too wiggly, too fake.;   But even a cynic won't deny thatthe flavors of mint and lamb are as compatible as Bogie and Bacall. You'vejust got to find the right formula. Instead of mint jelly, think mint sauce.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Food  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  LAMB AND MINT, A PERFECT MATCH  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Fast Lane; Charlyne Varkonyi writes about food for the Baltimore Sun.)  </MEMO><TEXT>     I worked with some adaptations of the classic Italian &quot;green sauce&quot; -- acombination of fresh mint and parsley, bread crumbs, vinegar and olive oil --and came up with a flavorful sauce that can complement chicken or fish as wellas lamb.;   The lamb is served with Italian cannellini beans, flavored withgarlic, peppers and basil.; BROILED LAMB CHOPS WITH CHUNKY MINT TOPPING; Chops:; 4 loin lamb chops, about 1 inch thick;  Salt, freshly ground pepper; Mint Sauce:; 1 large clove garlic; 1/2 cup fresh mint leaves, tightly packed;1/2 cup stemmed fresh Italian parsley, tightly packed; 1/4 cup fresh basilleaves, tightly packed; 3 tablespoons red wine vinegar; 1 tablespoon balsamicvinegar; 1/2 cup extra virgin olive oil; 1 cup fresh white bread crumbs; 1/2cup Italian-seasoned bread crumbs; 1 teaspoon salt;  To prepare chops, seasonthem to taste with salt and pepper.;   To make sauce, process garlic, mint,parsley, basil, vinegars and olive oil in food processor until mixed well. Addbread crumbs and mix until well-blended. Season to taste with salt. Setaside.;   Broil lamb chops in broiling pan about 4 inches from heating elementabout 5 minutes. Turn and broil another 4 to 5 minutes, depending on thicknessand how well you like your meat cooked. Serve topped with mint sauce. Makes 4servings.; (hbox); WARM CANNELLINI BEAN SALAD; 2 tablespoons extra virginolive oil; 2 cloves garlic, chopped; 3 green onions, sliced diagonally; 1/2red pepper, coarsely chopped; 1/2 green pepper, coarsely chopped; 1  14-ouncecan cannellini beans, drained but reserve 1/4 cup liquid; 1 tablespoon choppedfresh basil;  Salt, pepper;  Basil leaves for garnish;  Heat olive oil inlarge non-stick skillet until hot. Add garlic, onions and peppers and saute onmedium-high heat until peppers are soft. Add beans, reserved liquid and basiland heat through. Season to taste with salt and pepper. Garnish with basil.Makes 4 servings.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  CHARLYNE VARKONYI  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910821  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  August  </MONTH><PG.COL>  3C  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  386  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday, August 21, 199100234034,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>